content.text:
Laat me de automatische detectie-logica bekijken.

The user is talking about the "Foutje gezien? Meld het!" reaction panel (the slide-in panel). In it, there's a field "Welke tegel / sectie?" with a select dropdown that has a default option "— Automatisch gedetecteerd —". The user says the automatic detection doesn't work. Let me look at the code.

From what I read earlier in `index.html`, the `detectContext()` function is:

```javascript
function detectContext() {
    var el = document.querySelector('.dossier-detail-header h2, .breadcrumb-reset, .dossier-detail-titel');
    if (el) return el.textContent.trim();
    return 'de BeleidsBibliotheek';
}
```

This function sets `rpContext` (the bold text in "Je kijkt nu naar **—**"). But the `rpSectie` select dropdown has a default option with value "" and text "— Automatisch gedetecteerd —". When the form is submitted, it uses:

```javascript
var sectie = document.getElementById('rpSectie').value || ctx;
```

So if the select is left on "Automatisch gedetecteerd" (empty value), it falls back to `ctx` which comes from the `detectContext()` function, meaning the automatic detection should work by using the detected context as a fallback when no explicit selection is made.

But I'm noticing that `detectContext()` is searching for selectors that don't actually exist in the current HTML structure — like `.dossier-detail-header h2` and `.dossier-detail-titel` — when the actual title is in `#dossierTitel` with class `dossier-kop-titel`. The selector mismatch means the detection is failing. I should also check what `activeDossier` contains in app.js to see if the `rpSectie` select should be auto-populating based on the current dossier being viewed.

